result.execSummary:
The defendant Tammy M Jahns was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • OWI (4th), a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

All Financial obligations shall be paid to the Clerk of Courts within 60 days unless a payment plan is established. 
Shall submit a DNA sample and pay surcharge.

Defendant shall undergo an AODA Assessment and follow through with any recommendations resulting therefrom. Defendant shall undergo and follow through with any counseling/treatment as recommended by Agent or IDC Program professionals.

Defendant shall not consume alcohol or other intoxicants.  Defendant must maintain absolute sobriety. Defendant shall not go upon the premises of any establishment whose primary business activity involves the sale or distribution of alcoholic beverages, including bars, taverns, liquor stores and beer tents. 
Defendant shall not use/possess/control any controlled substances (without a valid prescription therefore) or drug paraphernalia, nor be in the presence of anyone who does.

Defendant shall successfully participate in and graduate from the Dodge County Impaired Driving Court (IDC) Program.
Defendant shall undergo random screens for drugs and alcohol to ensure absolute sobriety. Defendant acknowledges that she may be drug tested at any time. A missed test or a specimen that comes back "diluted" or "adulterated" will be considered "dirty" for which the defendant may be sanctioned. Repeated positive, diluted, or missed drug screens may be grounds for termination of the IDC Program.

Sign all releases authorizing treatment provider to contact any and all collateral sources including CCAP information, and such other releases as requested by agent.

Treatment provider to provide at least quarterly progress reports to agent and if, requested by Court, to the Court. 

Court includes sanctions for the following:
Failure to sign releases, jail until documents signed.
Any missed appointments/UAs without valid excuse = 10 days in jail
